\f1 \cf4 Client Abstract/ Problem Description:\cb1 \
\cb3 With the recent epidemic of the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) in China and its spread to other countries across the globe, including a few US states, we have been following instructions from the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). We\'92ve assembled isolation units, trained our staff on safety materials and quarantine procedures. With the likelihood of human to human transfer of the virus, we feel it would be prudent to take a more critical look at how to differentiate COVID-19 from influenza, the common cold and other viruses. So, we would like to develop a Data Science solution that could use data made available outside the medical center.\'a0 Depending on disease occurrence in Central Texas, we could in theory look at our real world patient data from our Electronic Medical Record system (EMR) for enhancing the solution or being used as test data.\
\cb1 \
\cb3 Business Understanding:\cb1 \
\cb3 Many of the symptoms associated with COVID-19 are similar to influenza, such as coughing, high fever and respiratory issues. While preventative measures, such as washing hands, avoiding contact with sick individuals and covering nose/ mouth when sneezing are useful to express, they are insufficient at determining who should be tested and how to diagnose. So the question we want to answer is:\
\cb1 \
\cb3 - Who should be tested and to what extent?\
\cb1 \
\cb3 Specifically, we need to understand if there is data available that can help ascertain key symptoms, combination of symptoms and other variables that can be used to assess whether patient is low, medium or high risk for COVID-19. Depending on the risk and symptoms, determining the type or types of testing that should be employed (fluid swab, blood lab and imaging) should also be determined.\'a0The audience/ user of this solution would be the clinicians (nurses, doctors\'85) providing care for new and existing patients.
\f0 \cf2  
