\
- What is the problem that you are trying to solve?\
\
Analytic Approach:\
Understanding that we are talking about determining whether a patient should be tested, i.e. yes/ no, we might want to consider a decision tree or considering predictive modeling. It really depends on what data is available, how it contrasts influenza/ other viruses. If the data also includes types of testing as well as severity and mortality, then we should also consider analyzing the relationship for determining value of testing as related to report turnaround and cost. Ideally we want a method for measuring whether implementing said solution makes a difference in diagnosing of COVID-19. The key question we want to answer is:\
\
- How can you use data to answer the question?\
\
Data Requirements:\
During this phase it is important to determine what kind of data is needed, specifically symptoms, lab results, testing methods and other content related to diagnoses being considered as part of the solution. The next dimension is determining where the data is coming from, such as the CDC, China, Johns Hopkins or Dell Med EMR. This phase should better determine whether a decision tree or predictive modeling is feasible. The key questions we want to answer are:\
\
- What data do you need to answer the question?\
- Where is the data coming from and how will you get it?\
\
Data Collection, Understanding and Preparation:\
During this next phase, we will be working with the data itself. We will collect it, understand how it is assembled, get rid of bad data and manipulate it based on our needs. This could be removing data that would lead to false positives (type 1 errors) and false negatives (type II, non-rejection of false null hypothesis). The data may exist in CSV format or maybe accessible via a relational database over JDBC.  Most likely the data will be pulled into a Jupyter Notebook, using Python, for working with the data.  The data can be visualized using Scala, both are available in IBM Watson Studio. This phase may iterate until the answers sought and the data is appropriately prepared. The key questions we want answered are:\
\
- Is the data collected representative of the problem to be solved?\
- What additional work is required to manipulate and work with the data?\
\
Modeling, Evaluation, Deployment and Feedback:\
This last set of steps in the methodology are around deriving an answer and validating that the solution answers the question defined during Business Understanding. This may include visualizing the data in different ways to more accurately answer when someone should be tested and using what methods. If outside data is being used for modeling the solution, can a training set be assembled for the hospital\'92s EMR. If all things prove out, then the solution is deployed for a set of clinicians to use and provide feedback. The IBM Watson Studio spark environment can be used for the modeling and evaluation of this solution. It includes Spark, PySpark (Python) and Scala. For statistical analysis RStudio can be used. This feedback will be gathered and used to adjust the model along with any other enhancements that are determined a priority. The key questions we strive to answer during this phase are:\
\
- In what way can the data be visualized to get to the answer that is required?\
- Does the model used really answer the initial question or does it need to be adjusted?\
- Can we put the model into practice?\
- Can we get constructive feedback into answering the question?\
